<H3> <TI>   Mercedes-Benz Increases Working Short Hours </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mercedes-Benz Increases Working Short Hours </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504174294 Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG in German 3 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Again More Working Short Hours at </F>
Mercedes-Benz"] 
  [Text] Stuttgart -- In order to ease the pressure caused 
by excessive personnel, Mercedes-Benz AG, Stuttgart, wants to 
use the instrument of working short hours more intensively again. 
  This was stated by Heiner Tropitzsch, the company's 
personnel 
chief, in an interview with STUTTGARTER NACHRICHTEN. Tropitzsch 
justified the change of course toward working short hours 
instead of reducing work time by referring to the new framework 
wage contract concluded in March. In this contract it was 
agreed that wages and salaries may be reduced in line with work 
time only if this applies to the entire company. 
  As a result, special work-time regulations for the 
individual 
factories have become very expensive compared with working short 
hours, Tropitzsch said. The industrial vehicle sector of the 
Stuttgart company is suffering very much, while business with 
passenger cars is improving. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

