<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Delegation Rebukes Zhirinovskiy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Delegation Rebukes Zhirinovskiy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504113494 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1000 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's delegation to the Council of Europe does 
not wish to attach much value to the statements made by Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy, the chairman of the Liberal Democratic Party. 
Vladimir Lukin, chairman of the foreign affairs committee of the 
Russian Duma, who heads the delegation visiting Finland, says 
that he takes Zhirinovskiy exactly as seriously as he deserves. 
Lukin, who arrived in Helsinki today, pointed out that 
Zhirinovskiy represented only a small section of the second 
chamber of the Russian parliament, i.e., the Duma. According to 
Lukin, Zhirinovskiy is behaving as if 80 percent of the 
parliamentary deputies were behind him. 
  The Finnish and Russian Council of Europe delegations began 
a 
two-day seminar in Helsinki today discussing Russia's prospects 
of becoming a member of the Council of Europe. Zhirinovskiy, 
who arrived in Finland already yesterday, thought that the 
Baltic countries still belonged to Russia. The statement is in 
sharp conflict with conditions for membership in the Council of 
Europe. David Atkinson, chairman of the committee that handles 
the Council's relations with countries outside the organization, 
sharply criticized Zhirinovskiy at the seminar that opened today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

