<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Views Participation in PFP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Views Participation in PFP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504141594 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1300 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Under the leadership of President Martti Ahtisaari, 
the government's Foreign Affairs Committee has discussed NATO's 
Partnership for Peace [PFP] initiative. Participation in the 
PFP program would, in line with earlier plans, concentrate on 
peacekeeping activities. Finland could offer peacekeeping 
training to those countries that want to take part in the UN's 
or the CSCE's peacekeeping operations. Finland is also prepared 
to take part in cooperation in the planning of peacekeeping 
operations. 
  The government stresses once again that Finland does not 
seek 
new defense solutions from the PFP and reiterates its doctrine 
of Finland's military nonalliance and an independent defense. 
In the government's view, NATO's PFP serves the stability of 
our continent and does not create new boundary lines. 

</TEXT>

