<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greece Calls Decision `Inappropriate' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greece Calls Decision `Inappropriate' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0604181294 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1740 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0604181294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ladies and Gentlemen, we will now read government 
spokesman Evangelos Venizelos' reaction to the EU [European 
Union] Commission's decision: Today's decision by the EU 
Commission is inappropriate and contradictory. While it 
recognizes the primary political character of the Skopje [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, FYROM] issue and the 
Greek measures of 16 February, in principle, it chooses the 
legal route to deal with the problem. Within this framework, we 
should note: First, the EU Commission is holding back until 13 
April. Second, the EU Commission is officially calling on 
Skopje to amend its Constitution and flag. The Greek Government 
expresses its regret, because this contradictory position by the 
EU Commission does not take into account the recent report from 
the UN secretary general to the Security Council or the 
mediation of Cyrus Vance. The relevant political initiatives by 
the European Union, which the Commission sees moving in parallel 
with Vance's work, and the mission of Matthew Nimetz [U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's special envoy on FYROM] are being 
jeopardized. And there is the additional danger that the EU 
Commission's decision today will encourage the intransigence of 
the Skopjean Government, which, due to its stance, should be on 
the receiving end of the international community's pressure. 
The possibility of the EU Commission appealing to the European 
Court is of secondary importance. In the final analysis, such a 
development will provide the opportunity for Greece's rich and 
strong legal arguments to unfold, arguments that complement the 
political base of the Greek positions. 
  The government spokesman's statement concludes: The Greek 
Government hopes that by 13 April and given that Vance has 
already issued his invitation for 11 April, the EU Commission 
can reach a more specific position that will aim to safeguard 
peace and stability in the region and reinforce the EU's common 
foreign policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

