<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vienna Turns Down UN Requests for Help in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vienna Turns Down UN Requests for Help in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704081694 Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network in German 
GMT 0500 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0704081694 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alfred Schwarz] </F>
  [Text] According to the Austrian authorities, a UN request 
for help with the reconstruction of Tuzla airport was turned 
down for technical reasons. Austria was asked to provide a 
certain type of stacker trucks, which the Austrian Army does not 
have. Purchasing such devices would have cost millions of 
Austrian schillings. 
  Another UN request, to train Pakistani troops in an Austrian 
training area, proved impossible for technical and legal 
reasons. The Pakistani UN soldiers should have been trained on 
old GDR tanks that are being used by UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Force] in Bosnia. But as Austria does not have such tanks, the 
army would have had to import them and train Austrian 
instructors to use them first, so as to be able to train the 
Pakistanis. Foreign troop maneuvers on Austrian territory would 
also have required a state treaty between Austria and the UN. 
This could not have been concluded within a few weeks, as would 
have been necessary, the Austrian Government said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

