<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Procurement Budget To Increase Slightly </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Procurement Budget To Increase Slightly </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704065694 Paris AFP in English 1737 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0704065694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 6 (AFP) -- French defence officials 
approved Wednesday [6 April] a military procurement budget for 
the next six years of 613 billion francs (107.5 billion 
dollars), equivalent to a 0.5 percent annual increase in real 
terms. 
  The 1995-2000 budget prepared by the Defence Council, 
chaired 
by President Francois Mitterrand, meant that some projects still 
in the research or development stage might be delayed, a defence 
official said. 
  But programmes relating to the nuclear-powered aircraft 
carrier Charles de Gaulle, the Rafale fighter aircraft and the 
Leclerc tank would be maintained, officials said. Some 
projects however were to be delayed or see their credits 
staggered over time, notably the NH-90 transport helicopter and 
the M5 nuclear ballistic missile. 
  The four-nations NH-90 helicopter, developed jointly with 
Germany, Italy and the Netherlands, is to be maintained though 
its cost will have to be cut by 20 to 30 percent, the officials 
said. 
  In addition to a second nuclear-powered aircraft carrier 
planned for after 1998, the Horizon frigate programme, developed 
jointly with Britain and Italy, could go ahead as early as next 
year. 
  The draft budget is to be approved by parliament early next 
year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

