<H3> <TI>   * Tighter Customs Controls on Border With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    * Tighter Customs Controls on Border With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94EN0271A Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 15 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> 94EN0271A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>
<F P=105>  Swedish </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Eastern Border Security More </F>
Important"] 
  [Excerpts] The National Bureau of Customs wants to start 
x-raying big rigs at the border crossing at Vaalimaa in order to 
make smuggling between Finland and Russia more difficult. 
Customs suggests that the state appropriate 60 million markkas 
in this year's budget. 
  The X-ray equipment would be used starting in 1998. [passage 
omitted] 
  The Bureau noted that Finnish Customs is prepared to 
implement the changes required by EU [European Union] 
membership. The geographical location of Finland is such that 
customs inspections must be maintained at most international 
airports and in most ports, even when Finland joins the EU. 
  "Guarding the eastern border becomes even more important 
than 
it previously was," noted Customs Director Juha Niskanen. 
  This year, Customs has not found any radioactive or other 
dangerous substances. In spite of that fact, the Customs Service 
is convinced that dangerous substances have been smuggled across 
the border from Russia and the Baltic states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

