<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Albanian Officials Hold Talks on Natural Gas Sale </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Albanian Officials Hold Talks on Natural Gas Sale </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0604115194 Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 5 Apr 94 p 40 </F>
<F P=103> NC0604115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] High-ranking officials of the Albanian Government 
with responsibility for energy issues had talks with the 
Greek-Russian company Promitheas Gas in Athens on the sale of 
natural gas to the neighboring country. 
  Heading the Albanian delegation was K. Meksi, bother of the 
Albanian prime minister. The meeting aimed at specifying the 
conditions for the supply of natural gas following the initial 
signing of a protocol between the Albanian Government and 
Promitheas Gas in November 1991. 
  According to a statement by the Greek-Russian company, 
Albania is particularly interested in developing the natural gas 
market as soon as possible. The supply of natural gas to the 
neighboring state will be achieved with the construction of a 
pipeline that will go through the area of Ptolemais, thus 
allowing for the supply of natural gas to the western Greek 
region. For the construction of the pipeline, a study is 
already underway with the support of the European Union through 
the PHARE [Poland-Hungary Assistance for the Reconstruction of 
the Economy] program. 
  According to reports, Albania is interested in the supply of 
1 billion cubic meters of natural gas per year to resume 
operations of fertilizer factories in southern Albania that 
today are idle due to a lack of raw materials. 
  As is known, Promitheas Gas was founded by the Russian 
company VEP Gasexport, the largest exporter of natural gas in 
the world, and the group of companies of Kopelouzou Brothers, 
which has the exclusive rights for the sale of natural gas that 
transits through Greece to third countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

