<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Public Order Minister Plans To Reform Police </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Public Order Minister Plans To Reform Police </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0704080394 Athens ATHENS NEWS in English 6 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> NC0704080394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ATHENS NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Stilianos Papathemelis, the public order minister, 
announced plans yesterday to introduce sweeping changes in the 
Greek police force, including the setting up of a special 
homicide unit and the right to form trade unions. 
  Draft legislation is to be tabled in parliament in the 
coming 
days, said Papathemelis, and will propose the establishment of 
powerful elite divisions in every department of the 
force--public order, security, traffic and consumer protection. 
The new system will be introduced as a pilot scheme next month 
in Athens, Thessaloniki and one regional town. Papathemelis 
said a national exam would be set for applicants seeking 
entrance to ordinary and officer police training schools. 
  Under the new proposals, police staff-management relations 
will be brought in line with the rest of the civil service. 
Transfers will only be allowed to take place once every year. 
If the bill is passed without significant amendments, 
Papathemelis said negotiations would begin with union leaders to 
allow police officers union representation. 

</TEXT>

