GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0604184994 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Turkey has said that Greece giving permission to 
the PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] to open a bureau in Athens 
is further new and concrete proof that this country sees nothing 
wrong with backing terrorism. 
  Answering a question on the issue, Foreign Ministry 
Spokesman 
Ferhat Ataman said that this adverse behavior by Greece, which 
came at a time when the realities behind the PKK terrorist 
organization's terrorism is better understood and banned in 
Europe, throws light on Greece's mentality as it concerns Turkey. 
  Ataman said: It is obvious that Greece never gained and 
never will gain anything from an approach that treats Turkey's 
enemy as its friend. Opening a terrorist bureau in Athens is 
against Greece's agreement regarding fighting terrorism as 
stipulated by international provisions. It is extremely 
disconcerting that Greece, which has itself been target of 
various terrorist organizations, is backing another terrorist 
organization. 
  Ataman noted: The Greek ambassador was called to our 
ministry in view of the developments in Athens. We described 
the incident as a hostile act, conveyed our reaction, and 
submitted a request that Greece abide by international 
requirements. 

</TEXT>

