<H3> <TI>   Stoiber Favors Partial EU Membership for Visegrad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stoiber Favors Partial EU Membership for Visegrad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704110494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0805 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From DDP/ADN's "Wirtschaftsdienst-Ost" economic service] </F>
  [Text] Budapest (ADN) -- Bavarian Minister-President Edmund 
Stoiber has urged partial membership of the European Union (EU) 
for the Visegrad states -- Hungary, Poland, the Czech Republic, 
and Slovakia. Speaking at a news conference in Budapest at the 
end of his visit to Hungary yesterday, Stoiber said the eastward 
expansion of the EU is of fundamental importance. On this issue 
he is in "relatively close agreement" with German Chancellor 
Helmut Kohl, who also spoke of a special relationship with the 
Visegrad countries. As a result in particular of the wave of 
migration from East Europe, the increase in organized crime, and 
a common asylum policy, these states should already have a place 
at the table of the Twelve, or eventually the Sixteen. 
  Stoiber arrived in Budapest with a delegation of leading 
Bavarian economic representatives yesterday morning. He 
conferred with Prime Minister Peter Boross, Defense Minister 
Lajos Fur, and Finance Minister Ivan Szabo. He also met with 
President Arpad Goncz and with Gabor Kuncze, the Alliance of 
Free Democrats candidate for the post of prime minister. 

</TEXT>

