<DOCNO> FBIS4-18605 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu067_h_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industry Official Warns of Excessive Export Laws </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Industry Official Warns of Excessive Export Laws </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704113594 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
7 Apr 94 p 15 </F>

<F P=103> AU0704113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Necker Opposes Excessive Export </F>
Controls"] 
  [Text] Bonn, 6 Apr -- Tyll Necker, president of the 
Federal Association of German Industry, has called on the 
Federal Government to abandon the special rules concerning 
export controls to preserve the competitiveness of German 
enterprises. For over four years, Germany has had special rules 
applicable to goods that can serve both a civilian and military 
purpose (dual use). "Now is the time to adopt a uniform 
Europewide control system," wrote Necker in a letter to Federal 
Industry Minister Guenter Rexrodt (FDP) [Free Democratic Party]. 
The Federal Government should display a readiness to reach 
compromises on a European scale and abandon its "attitude of 
isolation" that even made the adoption of the special rules 
difficult. Necker called for uniform controls within the 
European Union [EU] and the abolition of internal EU controls 
that collide with the single-market principle. The practice of 
issuing permits must also be brought into line with this 
principle, he said. 
  Necker was replying to a letter he received from Rexrodt at 
the beginning of March in which the FDP politician had suggested 
changes to German subsidiary regulations. Rexrodt had said that 
goods that do not appear on a control list and are destined for 
use in conventional armaments might be made exportable to only a 
small nucleus of countries. The same applies to services and 
the transfer of sensitive knowledge. Necker described these 
proposals as "merely the first step." On the other hand, 
Rexrodt's announcement that there should be greater clarity and 
faster decisions concerning the issue of export permits for 
military goods has been welcomed by industry. During the 
administrative removal of obstacles, regaining German 
competitiveness and abolition of one-sided disadvantages to 
competition must be the primary goal, Rexrodt wrote. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

