<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur Visits PRC; To Renew Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balladur Visits PRC; To Renew Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0604181594 Paris AFP in English 1805 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0604181594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 6 (AFP) -- French Prime Minister 
Edouard Balladur left here Wednesday [6 April] for China hoping 
to set the seal on renewed friendly relations between the two 
countries. 
  Balladur's visit comes three months after Paris and Beijing 
finally made up following a row over French warplane sales to 
Taiwan in 1992, which cost French firms hundreds of millions of 
dollars in lost trade with China. 
  His three-day visit to Beijing starting Thursday -- the 
first 
by a French Government leader since 1978 -- is aimed at bringing 
French companies back into the Chinese market. 
  Balladur said Tuesday it was in France's interest to have 
close and friendly relations with China, which he said was one 
of the world's great powers. 
  But he remained cagey in the run-up to his three-day visit 
to 
Beijing about whether he would raise the issue of human rights 
with Chinese leaders, despite pressure from two French 
humanitarian groups to do so. 
  Press rights campaign group Reporters sans Frontieres urged 
Balladur to intervene on behalf of 24 imprisoned Chinese 
journalists, and the Support Committee for the Tibetan People 
called for help to suffering Tibetan and Chinese people. 
  Balladur, speaking Tuesday on French television, said France 
could not remain indifferent to human rights issues but when 
questioned he said he had no further comment on the arrest of 
leading dissident Wei Jingsheng. 
  Balladur's visit is the latest in a line of visits by 
Western 
leaders renewing relations with Beijing after its violent 
suppression of the pro-democracy movement in 1989. 

</TEXT>

