<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Temporarily Halts Arms Deliveries to Turkey </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn Temporarily Halts Arms Deliveries to Turkey </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704141594 Hamburg DPA in German 1337 GMT 7 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0704141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The Federal Government has 
temporarily halted the already agreed deliveries within the 
framework of NATO equipment aid to Turkey. DPA learned this 
from government circles on Thursday [7 April]. This already 
applies to the next batch, which would have been due on 15 April 
and comprises optical gun sights and spare parts. 
  The decision was made in coordination between the 
Chancellor's Office, the Defense Ministry, and the Foreign 
Ministry. According to information provided by the responsible 
government circles, the decisive factor was the current 
examination of claims that Turkey is using materiel from German 
armament deliveries against Kurdish guerrillas in the country, 
which violates the NATO treaty. 
  NATO equipment aid, which is to be provided until the end of 
the year and is not to be resumed as of 1995, includes, among 
other things, 16 F4-F jets. This outdated photographic 
reconnaissance version of the double-jet U.S. combat fighter is 
being gradually discharged by the FRG Air Force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

