<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl Advocates Deportation of `Violent' Kurds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Advocates Deportation of `Violent' Kurds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704172694 Hamburg DPA in German 1621 GMT 7 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0704172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn/Munich (DPA) -- Chancellor Helmut Kohl has 
again come out in favor of deporting violent Kurds to their 
homeland. "I am not willing to bow to the terror of any group 
in the streets of Germany," Kohl said in an interview at his 
vacation resort in Bad Hofgastein, Austria, which was 
prereleased on Thursday [7 April]. 
  He added that if, in this case, it is the Kurds "who came to 
us with Turkish passports," they must be aware of the 
consequences. However, deportations may be carried out only to 
those countries where it is clearly obvious that "the necessary 
points have been ensured from the viewpoint of human rights." 
  Asked about the reservations by FRG Justice Minister Sabine 
Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger (Free Democratic Party of Germany) 
against the deportation of Kurds to Turkey, Kohl reportedly 
reacted with clear annoyance. "She does not represent in any 
way the opinion of the Federal Government in this matter, not to 
mention my own." Furthermore, it is not clear at all whether 
the minister's statements correspond to the opinion of the Free 
Democratic Party of Germany. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

