<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Warns on `Undesired' Forms of Protectionism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rexrodt Warns on `Undesired' Forms of Protectionism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704153994 Hamburg DPA in German 1416 GMT 7 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0704153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- In view of the latest conflicts 
between industrialized and developing countries about 
international trade advantages in the Third World, FRG Economics 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt (Free Democratic Party of Germany) 
warned against undeserved forms of new protectionism. At the 
Marrakesh meeting of the 121 GATT countries (from 12 to 15 
April), he will call on the trading partners to solve these 
problems in a discussion, which should be characterized by 
mutual understanding, says a statement by Rexrodt, who is 
currently in India, which was published in Bonn on Thursday [7 
April]. 
  The interrelations between trade and environment as well as 
trade and labor or social standards are highly political fields 
of negotiation, which are extremely sensitive for the developing 
countries. The minister had already come out against social 
dumping and against sanctions to have trade advantages of the 
developing countries reduced, e.g. in the textile sector, which 
they get because of their relatively low wages. 
  The Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] has called on 
the Federal Government to follow the United States and agree to 
the new World Trade Organization, WTO, the successor of GATT, 
only if certain minimum standards for working people's rights 
are agreed beforehand. SPD Deputy Hans Buettner stated: "Free 
trade union work, the right to freely negotiable minimum wages, 
as well as a minimum of labor protection are the precondition 
for a fair exchange of goods and services." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

