<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Says Berlusconi's Decision `Irrevocable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Says Berlusconi's Decision `Irrevocable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0604141594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1313 GMT 6 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0604141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "League Blames Berlusconi"] </F>
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 6 -- Antonio Tajani, spokesman 
for Forza Italia, in a statement reiterated that Berlusconi will 
not take part in any more negotiations with "those who have 
shown they do not respect alliances and agreements made before 
the elections and sanctioned by voters," referring to the 
Northern League. 
  Tajani also stressed that Berlusconi's decision to suspend 
all government-formation talks with his allies of the Northern 
League and the National Front was "irrevocable" and that the 
ball is now in the president's court. 
  According to the Constitution, President Oscar Luigi 
Scalfaro 
must name the prime minister, who in turn names his cabinet 
members, but Berlusconi until yesterday was conferring with 
potential government allies without waiting for a mandate from 
the head of state. 
  Berlusconi apparently gave up trying to pave some common 
ground between Bossi and National Alliance leader Gianfranco 
Fini and lost his patience with Bossi's radical and 
unpredictable changes in position. 
  Tajani in his statement conceded that "it is up to the 
president to interpret the election results and issue a mandate" 
to form a new government. "This is not a banana republic," said 
Tajani, adding that Bossi's "unlikely and useless" negotiations 
with his former arch-rivals of the Pact for Italy "only add 
confusion to confusion." 
  But Pact leader Mario Segni denied having been contacted by 
any officials of the Northern League. "I have not yet received 
any phone call from Bossi, nor from any other League official, 
so I cannot say when we will meet." 
  Segni did confirm however that he will be meeting with 
League 
officials but declined to reveal the agenda of the talks. 

</TEXT>

