<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "China/Italy: Shanghai Mayor in </F>
Rome"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 5 -- Bilateral trade was the 
leading topic Tuesday [5 April] when the mayor of Shanghai, 
Huang Ju, was received by Italian Prime Minister Carlo Azeglio 
Ciampi and Foreign Trade Minister Paolo Baratta at the Rome 
government's offices. 
  Future Italian programs and investments in China and 
"greater 
collaboration with the aim of consolidating positions gained" 
were discussed, a government communique said after the meeting. 
  Italian exports to China last year amounted to four trillion 
lire (2.45 billion dollars), mostly in industrial machinery, and 
China in 1993 jumped from 20th to 14th place among Italy's 
export markets, the communique said. 
  Mayor Huang Ju later had talks with Italian Foreign Minister 
Beniamino Andreatta focussing on prospects for the "particularly 
dynamic" area around Shanghai and possible "Italian 
participation in the development of the Pudong area," a foreign 
ministry communique said. 

</TEXT>

