<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Ease Export Regulations for East Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Ease Export Regulations for East Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804094394 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0836 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804094394 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hanover (ADN-Wirtschaftsdienst-Ost) -- The German 
Government evidently intends to make it easier to export high 
technology to the former East Bloc states. The HANNOVERSCHE 
ALLGEMEINE ZEITUNG reports that following the end of Cocom 
[Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls], the 
German Economics Ministry is currently looking into simplifying 
procedures for export permits. It will be possible in future to 
receive multiple export permits. Businesses would then only 
have to register their exports in retrospect. 
  Until now export procedures for high-performance computers 
or 
machine tools, for example, sometimes took over a year. Cocom, 
the agency responsible for this, was disbanded on 1 April. The 
Cocom list, specifying high technology items that were seen as 
sensitive in security policy terms and could thus not be sold to 
the former communist states, is thus no longer valid either. A 
special ruling had previously been needed for each individual 
transaction. 
  The Cocom states -- Japan, Australia, and all NATO states 
except Iceland -- have resolved to continue using the list as a 
basis for their decisions. The German Government wants to 
follow the United States in utilizing the new scope for 
maneuver, according to the paper. The new regulations will not, 
however, make arms exports any easier. 

</TEXT>

