<H3> <TI>   Ifo Predicts Industrial Production To Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ifo Predicts Industrial Production To Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0604165594 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 6 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU0604165594 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["ari"-signed report: "Foreign Demand Results in 2-Percent </F>
Increase in Industrial Production"] 
  [Text] Duesseldorf -- According to the Munich-based Ifo 
Institute, west German production will increase by approximately 
2 percent this year. Production of the processing industries 
declined by 7.7 percent in 1993. 
  Ifo expects a 5-percent real increase in export sales. 
Domestic sales, on the other hand, are expected to go up only 
slightly. 
  Positive stimuli by investments and stock cycles are clearly 
weakened by an increase in imports and declining private 
consumption. This was evident in the low domestic orders at the 
end of last year. 
  Forecasts for the major sectors of industry indicate 
differing results. Ifo expects a 1 to 2-percent decline (1993: 
minus 5.8 percent) in production of electrical goods, a 4 to 
5-percent decrease (minus 11.4 percent) in the textile industry, 
and an 8-percent decline (minus 9.9 percent) in the clothing 
industry. 
  West German mechanical engineering, which has lost 
approximately one-fifth of its production since 1990 (1993: 
minus 11.7 percent), can expect a slight increase of 
approximately 1 percent in 1994. 
  The electrical industry's capital goods sector will increase 
by some 3 percent (1993: minus 7.7 percent), which is partly a 
result of major supplies to eastern Germany. 
  In Ifo's view, production of pickup trucks and trucks, which 
declined by 25 percent in 1993, could stagnate even with foreign 
demand slightly increasing. Production of sedans and station 
wagons is, however, likely to increase by 5 percent, in spite of 
domestic supplies slightly declining (1993: minus 19.5 percent). 
  Due to stronger impulses from the domestic market, the 
chemical industry can expect production to increase by at least 
3 percent in 1994 (1993: minus 2.2 percent). Since steel 
consumption is going up again, the iron and steel producing 
industry is expected to increase by some 2 percent (1993: minus 
7 percent). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

