<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leotard Advocates Strikes Against Gorazde Attackers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leotard Advocates Strikes Against Gorazde Attackers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704163994 Paris AFP in English 1622 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0704163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 7 (AFP) -- French Defence Minister 
Francois Leotard called Thursday [7 April] for air strikes 
against Serb forces attacking the Bosnian Moslem enclave of 
Gorazde, saying the means to launch them were already in place. 
  "The planes are there, the pilots are there, it is perfectly 
possible, technically," he told a small group of journalists, 
saying that UN Security Council Resolution 824 could be invoked, 
if the "political will" existed. 
  The resolution, agreed on May 6 last year, allows for use of 
force in case of attacks on UN-designated safe areas in Bosnia, 
of which Gorazde is one of six. "I have made it known that we 
should enforce Resolution 824," he said. 
  Leotard said air strikes "are technically feasible, weather 
permitting," and stressed the importance of "enforcing all 
resolutions of the UN." 
  Fighting around the eastern Bosnian enclave has killed 64 
and 
left 301 wounded in the last nine days, according to Radio 
Sarajevo. It said Thursday that Serb forces were regrouping and 
that fighting was less intense. 
  Earlier Thursday a team of 11 UN observers and liaison 
officers reached the besieged enclave, after being held up en 
route by Serb forces at Rogatica, around 40 kilometres (25 
miles) from the enclave. 
  U.S. authorities, who have been reluctant to threaten the 
use 
of airpower over the situation in Gorazde, said Wednesday that 
they did not rule out the possibility of air strikes there. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

