<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis Rejects Lamb's Attempt To Change UN Document </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kliridhis Rejects Lamb's Attempt To Change UN Document </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0704170394 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0704170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis' meeting with Robert 
Lamb, the U.S. State Department special coordinator on Cyprus, 
concluded a short time ago. Lamb described the meeting as 
constructive. Replying to a relevant question, he said we should 
not get involved with what he called artificial timeframes. We 
should proceed, he noted, toward the implementation of the 
confidence-building measures. Lamb also said he would leave 
Cyprus tomorrow. 
  Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis said Lamb sought to 
bring changes to the UN document so that the talks can continue. 
Even if there are changes, Kasoulidhis said, [Turkish Cypriot 
leader] Rauf Denktas will ask for more, since he does not have 
the will for a Cyprus solution. The government spokesman said 
that during the meeting, President Kliridhis repeated that the 
Greek Cypriot side showed the highest possible degree of 
constructive willingness to accept the UN document. The Greek 
Cypriot side, he added, will accept no amendments to the 
document and no new document from the United Nations. 
Kasoulidhis said that our side did not ask for timeframes but 
stressed that since they exist they should be followed. The 
spokesman also said that anyone who tries to change the UN 
document will find himself in front of Denktas' policy of 
differing. Kasoulidhis then said that with the changes to the 
document, Lamb appears to hope that an agreement will be 
reached. This is a view, he said, with which the Greek Cypriot 
side disagrees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-18689 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu068_o_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-068 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lamb Departs; `Deadlock' Remains </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lamb Departs; `Deadlock' Remains </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0804073494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0700 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0804073494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Robert Lamb, U.S. State Department coordinator for 
the Cyprus issue, left Cyprus for Washington this morning 
without succeeding in ending the deadlock in the talks on the 
confidence-building measures. 
  Mr. Lamb yesterday had separate meetings with President 
Glavkos Kliridhis and Rauf Denktas. According to a statement by 
government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis, Mr. Lamb attempted to 
persuade the Greek Cypriot side that if certain changes were 
made to the documents, an agreement could be reached. President 
Kliridhis reiterated that our side would accept neither changes 
to the nonpaper nor a new document. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

