<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government's Position on FYROM Remains `Firm' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government's Position on FYROM Remains `Firm' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0704124794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0704124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today made 
it clear that Greece will proceed with removing the measures 
against Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM] only when the government of Kiro Gligorov 
gives three practical signs of goodwill, that is, on the 
symbols, border, and Constitution. The spokesman stressed that 
the Greek Government's positions on the issue of Skopje, which 
are known and firm, will be presented to UN mediator Cyrus Vance 
on 11 April in Washington by Ambassador Khristos Zakharakis, 
director general of the Foreign Ministry. 
  Venizelos said that the EU's [European Union] decision to 
refer Greece to the European Court of Justice undermines Vance's 
initiative and encourages Gligorov's intransigence, something 
that does not contribute to stability and security in the 
region. The government spokesman repeated that the EU 
Commission's decision violates the Union's solidarity and shows 
its contradictory character, because it cannot recognize the 
political character of Greece's countermeasures and pursue a 
diplomatic initiative with Dutch Commissioner Hans van den Broek 
on the one hand, and decide to follow the judicial route on the 
other. The positive aspect that the Greek Government has 
recognized in yesterday's decision, Venizelos concluded, is that 
the European Union calls on Skopje to change its flag and amend 
its constitution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

