Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister `Pessimistic' About FYROM Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister `Pessimistic' About FYROM Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0704161194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0704161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Referring to the latest developments in the issue 
of Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM], 
government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said the Greek 
Government has shown signs of being flexible and conciliatory 
but cannot deviate from its basic stated positions. He added 
that the Greek measures will be lifted if and when the Skopjean 
Government gives tangible proof of the goodwill signs to which 
repeated references have been made. 
  The spokesman described the European Commission's decision 
yesterday [to refer Greece to the European Court of Justice] as 
inappropriate and contradictory and said he hopes the Commission 
will finally change its view. He said: If this does not 
happen, we will have the chance to present our strong judicial 
arguments in court. 
  The spokesman noted that the European Commission should have 
considered the UN secretary general's recent report to the 
Security Council, which notes that the continuing dispute 
between Greece and Skopje causes international tension and 
endangers peace in the region. Venizelos said U.S. Special 
Presidential Envoy Ambassador Matthew Nimetz's initiative 
remains open and that Greek Ambassador in Washington Khristos 
Zakharakis will meet UN mediator Cyrus Vance. The spokesman 
stressed that yesterday's decision violates the rule of communal 
solidarity. 
  Commenting on yesterday's developments in the Skopje issue, 
Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias and New Democracy Chairman 
Miltiadhis Evert stressed that the national front must remain 
united. Papoulias and Evert met at noon today at Evert's 
request. 
  Afterward Papoulias appeared pessimistic about developments 
in the national issue but stressed that during Zakharakis' 
meeting with Vance in New York on 11 April, the Greek side would 
mainly be concerned with breaking the deadlock. He added that 
the Greek people stand firm in the battle that Greece is waging 
following recent developments. 
  Asked about Political Spring Chairman Andonios Samaras' 
request that the government take additional measures against 
Skopje, Papoulias indirectly rejected Samaras' proposals, saying 
the government is now preparing for the new phase that has been 
created. 
  Asked about the differences between the new Vance plan and 
what was agreed in the United Nations during the New Democracy's 
term, Papoulias said the difference lies in the separation of 
the name issue from the confidence-building measures, adding 
that the international mediator's views coincide with the Greek 
views. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

