<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi on Privatizations, State Role in Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciampi on Privatizations, State Role in Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0704151794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1358 GMT 7 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0704151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Any Government Can Continue </F>
Privatizations, Ciampi"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 7 -- Privatizations begun under 
his administration can continue under either a left-wing or a 
right-wing government, according to acting Prime Minister Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi. 
  "Privatizations are compatible with a government of the 
right 
or of the left," Ciampi said in a public television interview, 
adding that two positive results will come from privatizations: 
"improved company management and the creation of a wider 
financial market, which this country needs." 
  The state will not "disappear" from the economic field, 
Ciampi said: "it will remain part of the economy because it's 
good for the state to be present in some sectors and because it 
is the state that sets rules and enforces the rules, leaving the 
private sector free to work within these rules." 
  Deregulation, according to Ciampi, means "greater freedom to 
operate, not the total abandonment of all rules." 
  Ciampi stressed that the central bank must retain its 
autonomy and that the government must provide "direction and 
guarantees." 
  Turning back to privatizations, Ciampi said that when his 
government was formed in spring 1993, there had been talk of 
privatizations for years but that nothing had been done. Now 
they are under full steam, he claimed, citing the sale of Comit, 
Credit and part of IMI [Italian Institute for Financing Personal 
and Real Property], and plans for the sale of STET [Turin 
Telephone Finance Company] and SME, as well as part of the steel 
sector. 
  He also predicted that fiscal pressure would drop one 
percent 
this year. 

</TEXT>

