<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Foreign Minister Visits, Signs Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukraine Foreign Minister Visits, Signs Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0704190794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0704190794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] A visa waiver agreement covering diplomatic and 
special passports was signed between Turkey and Ukraine today. 
Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko arrived on a one-day 
official visit in Turkey today. The visiting minister first met 
with Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin. A visa waiver agreement 
covering diplomatic and special passports was signed after the 
meeting. The agreement was signed by Cetin and Zlenko. 
  The disarmament of the Black Sea, matters pertaining to oil 
and natural gas, and President Suleyman Demirel's upcoming visit 
to Ukraine in May were among the issues discussed during the 
meeting, Cetin explained. Cetin announced that agreement was 
reached for Turkey to open consulates in Crimea and Odessa and 
for Ukraine to open a consulate in Istanbul. Zlenko, in turn, 
said that the visa waiver agreement will create an atmosphere of 
trust and sincerity between the two countries. 
  Zlenko and the delegation accompanying him were later 
received by Demirel. According to a statement issued by the 
President's Press Center, the visiting minister relayed to 
Demirel a message from Ukrainian President Kravchuk and noted 
that his government will be pleased to see Demirel in Ukraine 
next month. Demirel also said that he will be pleased to visit 
Ukraine. During the meeting, the president expressed Turkey's 
readiness to help Ukraine in returning the Crimean Tartars to 
their homeland. Views were also exchanged during the meeting on 
regional and international issues concerning the two countries, 
and Demirel announced that the necessary political will exists 
for the development of relations with Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

