<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Plans Evacuations From Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Plans Evacuations From Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Decision Forthcoming </H4>

<F P=102> LD0804110794 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 0900 
GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0804110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The first news of the morning in Kigali has just 
reached us. To sum up, there is no change. The fighting is 
continuing in the streets of the Rwandan capital. Press 
correspondents on the spot report, I quote, that fighting is 
raging and that UN officials fear that Hutu-Tutsi clashes may 
spread beyond the capital. There is also confirmation of the 
involvement of the Rwandan opposition in these hostilities. 
Yesterday the troops of the Rwandan Patriotic Front left the 
location where they were taking cover and are involved in 
exchanges of fire with the regular army troops. The toll of the 
clashes is particularly high, according to a UN official. In 
Kigali, fires are raging at certain points, and hand-to-hand 
fighting has been witnessed on the streets of the capital. 
  In Brussels, a first review of the situation was carried out 
yesterday evening and continued into the early hours of the 
night. At midday or perhaps early this afternoon, the government 
is going to resume its review of the situation in the presence 
of Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene, who has returned from 
abroad. Foreign Minister Willy Claes will return later today. 
Any decision concerning evacuation that might have to be made 
will probably be announced in the afternoon. In any case, since 
yesterday, paracommando troops have been preparing for every 
eventuality. There appears to be a general mobilization this 
morning in the Belgian paratroop camp, and the paratroopers of 
Flawinne barracks were recalled very early this morning. The 
situation is exactly the same at Stokkem barracks, where the 
soldiers have also been recalled. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

