<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNHCR Suspends Airbridge Between Ancona, Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNHCR Suspends Airbridge Between Ancona, Sarajevo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104104194 Paris AFP in English 1008 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1104104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ancona, Italy, April 11 (AFP) -- The UNHCR on 
Monday [11 April] suspended its airlift between the Italian Air 
Force base at Ancona to the Bosnian capital Sarajevo, a 
spokeswoman for the UN aid agency said here. 
  Speaking at Ancona airport, Antonella Gesulfo from the 
office 
of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, said the organisation 
was awaiting "the next developments" before deciding whether or 
not to resume the airlift. 
  The decision follow's Sunday's airstrikes by two U.S. F-16 
fighters against Bosnian Serb forces attacking the UN-protected 
Moslem enclave of Goradze in eastern Bosnia-Hercegovina. 
  In Geneva, UNHCR spokesman Ron Redmond said the 20 flights 
planned for Monday as a "precaution," adding that "Tuesday we 
will reassess the situation." [sentence as received] 
  The decision was taken by the UNHCR and the UN Protection 
Force in Bosnia, and representatives of the six countries -- 
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Sweden and the 
United States -- operating the air bridge. 
  A Canadian C-130 aircraft which was being used to airlift 
injured Bosnians out of Bosnia has left for East Africa to take 
part in the evacuation of foreigners from Rwanda. 

</TEXT>

