<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgia-Abkhazia Talks Postponed Until 12 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Georgia-Abkhazia Talks Postponed Until 12 April </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804153794 Paris AFP in English 1512 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0804153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 8 (AFP) -- Talks on the deployment of 
a peacekeeping force for the separatist Georgian region of 
Abkhazia have been postponed until next Tuesday [12 April], UN 
spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said. 
  The talks, scheduled to have started Friday, follow a 
ceasefire signed Monday by Georgia and Abkhazian separatists 
which allows for multinational peacekeeping force to be sent to 
the breakaway republic in northwest Georgia. 
  The meeting, to be headed by Butrus-Ghali's special 
representative Eduard Brunner, is to deal only with military 
aspects of the agreement such as the number and deployment of 
the maximum 2,500 troops. 
  The trickier question of Abkhazia's status will be discussed 
in Geneva on April 19 at a meeting of the two sides, Russian and 
UN facilitators and members of the Conference on Security and 
Cooperation in Europe, the spokeswoman said. 
  Last week's ceasefire agreement aimed to help the return of 
some 250,000 Georgian civilians who have fled the area in more 
than a year of war, and holds out the possibility of 
far-reaching autonomy for Abkhazia within Georgia. 
  Talks on the return of refugees began Friday in Sochi in 
Russia, presided over by Russia and the UN High Commission for 
Refugees [UNHCR], Gastaut said. 
  On Thursday, the two sides accused each other of violating 
the ceasefire which had been signed in the presence of UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali and Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev. 

</TEXT>

