<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Claes on Rwandan Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Claes on Rwandan Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Backs UNAMIR in Rwanda </H4>

<F P=102> LD1004160894 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1500 
GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1004160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Belgian foreign affairs minister has confirmed 
that there have been Belgian civilian victims in the clashes in 
Rwanda: Three Belgian civilians were killed on 7 April. This 
was learned only today: The precise circumstances of their death 
are not yet known. 
  Following on from these serious disturbances in Rwanda, and 
in particular in Kigali, people sometimes wonder about the role 
of the Belgian troops who have been there for several months as 
part of the UN peacekeeping forces, as soldiers of UNAMIR [UN 
Assistance Mission in Rwanda]. But, like all UN troops, these 
Belgian soldiers have a very strict mandate from the United 
Nations. On television this lunchtime in the (Mise au Point), 
Foreign Minister Willy Claes stressed once again the extension 
of the mandate of the UN forces in Rwanda: 
  [Begin Claes recording] I believe that we really were not 
wrong when we sent the troops. We were one of those promoting 
the peace process, and we have to back it up now. As far as I 
am concerned, I think the mandate was too restricted, and we 
need a thorough debate on the UN mandate, and therefore, on the 
implementation of this over restrictive mandate. Also, the 
weaponry was insufficient. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

