<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Criticizes Deportation of Kurds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Criticizes Deportation of Kurds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1004191394 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
9 Apr 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> AU1004191394 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["wtr"-signed commentary: "Sheer Populism"] </F>
  [Text] It is sheer populism that not only the chancellor 
but also his challenger in the elections now demand that violent 
Kurds be deported to Turkey. Admittedly, Scharping is linking 
his demand more clearly and precisely to Ankara respecting human 
rights than does Kohl, but this is not the way to do it! 
Presenting oneself as tough for the sake of right-wing voters 
and dangling human rights guarantees in front of liberal and 
thoughtful people at the same time is dangerous. It is 
dangerous, because it creates the impression that it only 
requires a few talks with Ankara to remove the obstacles to 
deportations that have quite rightly been built up by the law on 
foreigners and the Geneva Convention on Refugees. 
  Reality looks quite different. Turkey has violated every 
human rights agreement it has ever signed. Turkey is using the 
fight against the Workers Party of Kurdistan to complete its 
political, cultural, and social oppression of the Kurds. And, 
in Turkey, promises of the civilian government do not carry much 
weight. In the Kurdish areas -- and not only there -- the Army 
has the final say. 
  Politicians should be careful not to create the impression 
that the problem is easy to solve. Otherwise they might 
pressure themselves into having to violate international 
obligations in order to keep their promises. No, there must be 
an end to suggestions that Turkey is a country to which people 
can be deported. Anyone committing an offense in Germany must 
be tried in Germany and put in German prisons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-18770 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu069_j_94002" </HT>


