<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tehran, Rome Hold Talks on Debt Rescheduling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tehran, Rome Hold Talks on Debt Rescheduling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004133694 Tehran IRNA in English 1213 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome, April, 10, IRNA -- Iran and Italy are now 
engaged in financial negotiations focusing on rescheduling 
Iran's debts to Italian firms, Iran's ambassador here, Majid 
Hedayat-Zadeh Razawi said Saturday [9 April]. 
  Razawi told IRNA that Italy is Iran's third largest trade 
partner and Iran is Italy's third largest supplier of crude oil 
with trade between the two countries standing at drls. 3 billion 
annually. 
  The issue can be settled if Italian creditor companies agree 
to reschedule the debts owed by Iran to them in a way that Iran 
can pay off its debts in a four year period starting two years 
after such an agreement is reached, he said. 
  "As a matter of fact, no figure has been mentioned in the 
negotiations or in a letter of understanding inked by the two 
countries.... What is important is the topic of discussion and 
an overall agreement," he said. 

</TEXT>

