<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demonstrations at U.S. Embassy, UN Site Over Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demonstrations at U.S. Embassy, UN Site Over Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1004184894 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 10 apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1004184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Excerpt] The massacres perpetrated by the Serbs in the 
town of Gorazde in Bosnia-Herzegovina were condemned in 
demonstrations held in various cities, especially in Ankara and 
Istanbul. 
  Thousands of people who gathered in Zafer Square in Kizilay, 
Ankara, chanted slogans condemning the Serbian massacres and the 
attitude of the United Nations. The citizens then started 
marching along Ataturk Boulevard to the UN representation in 
Ankara. They continued their protests there as well. Certain 
provocateurs in the crowd hurled stones, shattering some of the 
windows of the UN building. Despite these provocations, the 
people proceeded to Kocatepe Mosque following the appeasing 
remarks of Ankara Governor Erdogan Sahinoglu and Ankara Security 
Director Orhan Tasanlar, who arrived at the scene of the 
incident. 
  During the march, stones were thrown shattering the windows 
of the TRT General Directorate building, the U.S. Embassy, and 
the Russian Commercial Attache's Office. Some individuals 
climbed over the iron fence of the U.S. Embassy and entered the 
garden. They posted a flag at the main entrance of the U.S. 
Embassy and then left the garden. 
  In a statement to TRT, Sahinoglu said that efforts are under 
way to determine who is responsible for directing the course of 
events. Asking the citizens not to heed such provocations, 
Sahinoglu noted: I believe that with regard to international 
relations, which are sensitive, it is appropriate for us to 
display attitudes that are more careful, self-sacrificing, and 
befitting our traditions. I particularly ask our people not to 
heed provocations and such rumors. 
  The recent attack against Gorazde was also condemned in a 
demonstration held in Istanbul's Taksim Square. Groups, which 
gathered in Taksim Square at noon, shouted various slogans 
against the Serbs. The police did not intervene in the 
demonstration, which was held without a permit. Certain people 
attempted to behave in an excessive manner, however, attacking 
members of the press, who were filming the meeting, including 
TRT teams. The groups, which remained in Taksim Square for 
about three hours, later marched along Istiklal and Cumhuriyet 
Streets. Intensive security measures were adopted during these 
marches. A group proceeding towards Harbiye chanted slogans 
against TRT in front of the TRT Istanbul Radio building. The 
demonstrators shouted slogans against the UN, Israel, and the 
United States. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-18798 </DOCNO>
