<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Foreign Minister Arrives on Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Foreign Minister Arrives on Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1004161694 Ankara ANATOLIA in Turkish 1515 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1004161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara (AA) -- Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on 
Peres arrived on a two-day official visit in Ankara today. 
  The Israeli foreign minister was received at Ankara's 
Esenboga Airport by Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin. In an 
airport statement, Cetin recalled that the framework of the 
relations between the two countries was outlined in a 
declaration during his visit to Tel Aviv in November. Pointing 
out that Peres is an important and well-known personality in the 
region as well as in the world, Cetin reported that bilateral 
relations, regional issues, and the Middle East peace process 
will be discussed during the talks in Ankara. 
  Turkey and Israel are two countries based on parliamentary 
democracy and free market economy, Cetin remarked. Recalling 
that the Israeli president also visited Turkey some time ago, 
Cetin noted that these visits greatly contribute to bilateral 
relations. 
  Cetin declared that Peres plays an important role in the 
Middle East peace process and said that the visit will add a new 
dimension to Turkish-Israeli relations. 
  In his turn, Peres stated that the Middle East peace process 
has reached the stage of implementation, pledging that from now 
on his country will work for the economic development of the 
region to benefit of the people living in this region. 
  Peres said that Turkey is a bridge between the Middle East, 
Europe, and Asia, and it is the most contemporary country among 
the Muslim countries where religion and state are separated. 
Remarking that the two countries share a common history as well 
as common interests, the Israeli foreign minister underlined the 
great potential for cooperation in bilateral relations. 
  Meanwhile, in reply to a question, Cetin declared that 
Turkey 
is ready to contribute to the Middle East peace process in every 
possible way if both sides demand it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

