<H3> <TI>   Joint Defense Group Meeting With U.S. Ends </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Joint Defense Group Meeting With U.S. Ends </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0904060794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0904060794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] A high-level joint defense group meeting between 
Turkey and the United States ended in Ankara today. A 
memorandum of understanding on the meeting was signed by General 
Ahmet Corekci, deputy chief of the General Staff, and Charles 
Freeman, U.S. under secretary of defense. 
  In a statement at the signing ceremony, Corekci said that 
the 
Turkish Armed Forces' power structure for the 21st century and 
their long-term needs for military equipment were determined. 
Freeman, in turn, noted that his country regards Turkey as the 
third largest country in Europe. 
  Answering reporters' questions, Freeman declared that his 
country views the PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] as a 
terrorist organization and does not support it. He remarked 
that he had the opportunity to observe more closely Turkey's 
just struggle against terrorism and its respect for human rights 
in waging this struggle. 

</TEXT>

