<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plans for Evacuation of Rwanda Implemented </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plans for Evacuation of Rwanda Implemented </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Transport Planes Depart </H4>

<F P=102> LD0904074794 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 0700 
GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0904074794 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The first planes have taken off this morning. The 
operation to evacuate 1,500 Belgian nationals from Rwanda was 
authorized by the government. The first Hercules C-130s took 
off this morning. For now, they mostly seem to be carrying 
equipment. We're joined from Melsbroek by Thierry Belfroi. Have 
more planes been taking off? 
  [Melroi] Yes, four planes have taken off since 0715. Convoys 
have been arriving at the military airport here in Meulebroek 
throughout the night -- military equipment and jeeps. There 
have not yet been any troops. The latest news we have received 
from the Tielen barracks from where the paracommandos are 
expected to arrive at about 0930 this morning is that their 
departure from the barracks has been delayed by at least one or 
two hours. Journalists are being kept away from the barracks, 
and it is very difficult to get any information. There are 
stilll four C-130s on the apron ready to take off with 
equipment, and two Boeing 727s, which are waiting to take off 
with the troops which are expected. We're also expecting troops 
from Flawinne in the course of the afternoon. 

</TEXT>

